# Repository Guidelines

This repository tracks Hyprland configuration. Keep changes small, well-explained, and focused so downstream reloads stay reliable. Use this guide as the baseline for contributions.

## Project Structure & Module Organization
- `mod-hyprland.conf` is the entry point; it sources the other module-specific files in the load order shown inside it.
- Core configuration lives in focused files such as `monitors.conf`, `keybinds.conf`, `input.conf`, and `style.conf`; add new topics by creating a dedicated file and sourcing it from the module list.
- Runtime assets (wallpapers, scripts) belong alongside their consuming config, and any experimental variants should sit under `backups/` with a clear timestamp suffix.

## Build, Test, and Development Commands
- `hyprctl reload` — reload Hyprland after editing to validate syntax and apply changes.
- `hyprctl keyword source ~/.config/hypr/mod-hyprland.conf` — force-read the main config when testing new include chains.
- `hyprpaper reload` — refresh wallpaper settings after editing `hyprpaper.conf`.
- `git diff` — review pending changes before staging to avoid accidental rewrites of generated sections.

## Coding Style & Naming Conventions
- Follow Hyprland’s `keyword=value` syntax with single spaces around commas for readability.
- Group related settings under banner comments (`################`) and keep indentation flat unless a block requires nested braces.
- Use descriptive `$variable_names` for reusable commands; prefer lowercase with underscores (e.g., `$launcher_app`).
- Inline comments should explain intent, not restate the obvious command; keep them on the same line when short.

## Testing Guidelines
- After `hyprctl reload`, watch `~/.local/share/hyprland/hyprland.log` for parsing errors or warnings.
- Validate keybinds with `hyprctl dispatch keyword` dry runs before enabling disruptive shortcuts.
- When touching monitors or workspace logic, verify on all attached outputs by toggling with `hyprctl monitors`.

## Commit & Pull Request Guidelines
- Use Conventional Commit prefixes (`feat:`, `fix:`, `docs:`) followed by a short imperative summary (≤72 chars).
- Describe the rationale, testing steps, and any follow-up tasks in the PR body; include screenshots for visual tweaks.
- Cross-link related issues or tickets and mention required restart steps so reviewers know how to validate locally.



